notesStmt.note: 1* contains a Latin translation of the colophon from the folio 209r.
2* is a Latin index to the contents of the volume.
Folios 84v-146v have marginal additions with Rashi's commentary on Psalms, due to a 15th century hand.
Manuscript description based on Margoliouth, G.: Catalogue of the Hebrew and Samaritan Manuscripts in the British Museum, London 1965.

msContents.summary: Rashi's commentary on the Five Scrolls, the Former and Latter Prophets, and Yosef Ḳara's commentary on Job.

supportDesc.extent: 235 folios (+ 2 unfoliated paper flyleaves, 1 unfoliated vellum flyleaf and 2 foliated vellum flyleaves at the beginning, and 2 unfoliated paper flyleaves at the end). Part I: Folios 1r-27v. Part II: Folios 28-209. Part IV:;

layoutDesc.layout: Part I: 2 column(s); ruled lines: 34; written lines: 33; Uniform layout. Part II: 2 column(s); ruled lines: 34; written lines: 33; Uniform layout. Part III: 2 column(s); ruled lines: 47; written lines: 46; Uniform layout. Pricking and pen-ruling visible. Part IV: 3 column(s); ruled lines: 25; written lines: 24; Pricking and hard-point ruling visible.

scriptDesc.scriptNote: Part I: Ashkenazi (French?) semi-cursive script of 16th century. Mosheh Merḳis: inscirbed with his name in the colophon, folios 23v, 27r. The name 'Mosheh' has been marked with pen designs, e.g. folio 15r.Part II: Ashkenazi (French?) semi-cursive script of 13th century. Yosef ben Natan: inscribed with his name, together with the name of Shimshon ben Yehudah, in the colophon, 1257, folio 209r.Part III: Ashkenazi semi-cursive of 13th century.Part IV: Ashkenazi (French) square of c15th century.

binding.p: Post-1600; Harleian binding with gold-tooling, the Harley coat of arms in the centre.

origin.origPlace: Part I: Italy Part II: France Part III: France Part IV: France

history.provenance: Acquisition: The Harley Collection, formed by Robert Harley (b. 1661, d. 1724), 1st earl of Oxford and Mortimer, politician, and Edward Harley (b. 1689, d. 1741), 2nd earl of Oxford and Mortimer, book collector and patron of the arts. Edward Harley bequeathed the library to his widow, Henrietta Cavendish, née Holles (b. 1694, d. 1755) during her lifetime and thereafter to their daughter, Margaret Cavendish Bentinck (b. 1715, d.1785), duchess of Portland; the manuscripts were sold by the Countess and the Duchess in 1753 to the nation for £10,000 (a fraction of their contemporary value) under the Act of Parliament that also established the British Museum; the Harley manuscripts form one of the foundation collections of the British Library.
